106	    .formula-box { font-size: 1rem; padding: 1rem; }
107	  }
108	</style>
109	</head>
110	<body>
111	<div class="container">
112	
113	<h1>Lesson 0001: The UCT Selection Formula</h1>
114	<p class="subtitle">The engine at the heart of MCTS — how to choose which branch to explore.</p>
115	
116	<!-- ─── SECTION 1: Why Selection Matters ─── -->
117	<h2>1. Why Selection Is the Brain of MCTS</h2>
118	<p>
119	  In the MCTS cycle, <strong>Selection</strong> is where the algorithm decides <em>which path</em> to descend. A naive selection — always picking the move with the highest win rate — would never discover hidden strengths of unexplored branches. A random selection would be too slow to converge.
120	</p>
121	<p>
122	  The solution is the <strong>UCT</strong> (Upper Confidence Bound applied to Trees) formula. It treats each move from a game state as a <em>multi-armed bandit</em> problem: you have several slot machines (moves), each paying out wins at some unknown rate. UCT tells you which machine to pull next.
123	</p>
124	
125	<!-- ─── SECTION 2: The Formula ─── -->
126	<h2>2. The UCT Formula (Anatomy)</h2>
127	
128	<div class="formula-box" id="formula-box">
129	  UCT(s, a) = <span class="expl-term">w(s,a) &frasl; n(s,a)</span> + <span class="explr-term">C<sub>p</sub> &times; &radic;( ln N(s) &frasl; n(s,a) )</span>
130	</div>
131	
132	<table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">
133	  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #dee2e6;">
134	    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Term</th>
135	    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Meaning</th>
136	    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Role</th>
137	  </tr>
138	  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
139	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color: #e94560;"><strong>w(s,a) / n(s,a)</strong></td>
140	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Win rate of action <em>a</em> from state <em>s</em></td>
141	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;"><span style="color:#e94560;">Exploitation</span> — favour moves known to win</td>
142	  </tr>
143	  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
144	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color: #0f3460;"><strong>&radic;( ln N(s) / n(s,a) )</strong></td>
145	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Uncertainty bonus — shrinks as we visit <em>a</em> more</td>
146	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;"><span style="color:#0f3460;">Exploration</span> — favour moves tried fewer times</td>
147	  </tr>
148	  <tr>
149	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color: #533483;"><strong>C<sub>p</sub></strong></td>
150	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Exploration constant (tunable, default ~&radic;2)</td>
151	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;"><span style="color:#533483;">Balance</span> — how much weight to give exploration</td>
152	  </tr>
153	</table>
154	
155	<p>
156	  <strong>When n(s,a) = 0</strong> (the move has never been tried), the formula returns +&infin; — it <em>always</em> selects an unvisited child. This ensures every legal move is sampled at least once before exploitation dominates.
157	</p>
158	
159	<div class="callout">
160	  <strong>&#128161; Key Insight:</strong> The exploration term &radic;( ln N(s) / n(s,a) ) uses the <em>parent's</em> total visits N(s) in the numerator, not the child's. This means a move that looks average but has been visited far fewer times than its siblings gets a large exploration bonus.
161	</div>
162	
163	<!-- ─── SECTION 3: Interactive Demo ─── -->
164	<h2>3. Interactive Demo: Tuning C<sub>p</sub></h2>
165	<p>
166	  Below is a root node with four possible moves (A&ndash;D). Each has been visited a different number of times with different win rates. Adjust the <strong>C<sub>p</sub></strong> slider to see which move UCT selects.
167	</p>
168	
169	<div class="slider-group">
170	  <label for="cp-slider">Exploration Constant C<sub>p</sub></label>
171	  <input type="range" id="cp-slider" min="0" max="5" step="0.1" value="1.41">
172	  <div class="value-display" id="cp-value">C<sub>p</sub> = 1.41</div>
173	  <div class="hint">Low (&lt;0.5) = exploit aggressively &nbsp;|&nbsp; High (&gt;3) = explore aggressively</div>
174	</div>
175	
176	<div class="tree-viz" id="tree-viz">
177	  <div class="tree-row">
178	    <div class="tree-node root-node">
179	      <div class="label">Root N=100</div>
180	    </div>
181	  </div>
182	  <div class="tree-row" id="children-row">
183	    <div class="tree-node child-node" id="child-A" data-wins="8" data-visits="10">
184	      <div class="label">Move A</div>
185	      <div class="stat">w=8 n=10 (80%)</div>
186	      <div class="uct-val">UCT: —</div>
187	    </div>
188	    <div class="tree-node child-node" id="child-B" data-wins="35" data-visits="50">
189	      <div class="label">Move B</div>
190	      <div class="stat">w=35 n=50 (70%)</div>
191	      <div class="uct-val">UCT: —</div>
192	    </div>
193	    <div class="tree-node child-node" id="child-C" data-wins="18" data-visits="30">
194	      <div class="label">Move C</div>
195	      <div class="stat">w=18 n=30 (60%)</div>
196	      <div class="uct-val">UCT: —</div>
197	    </div>
198	    <div class="tree-node child-node" id="child-D" data-wins="2" data-visits="10">
199	      <div class="label">Move D</div>
200	      <div class="stat">w=2 n=10 (20%)</div>
201	      <div class="uct-val">UCT: —</div>
202	    </div>
203	  </div>
204	</div>
205	
206	<div class="callout">
207	  <strong>Try it:</strong> Set C<sub>p</sub> = 0. Move B (70% win rate) is selected — pure exploitation. Now set C<sub>p</sub> to 5.0. The low-win, low-visit Move D now gets the highest UCT score because its uncertainty bonus is huge.
208	</div>
209	
210	<!-- ─── SECTION 4: Worked Example ─── -->
211	<h2>4. Worked Example (By Hand)</h2>
212	
213	<p>Suppose we're at a root with <strong>N(s) = 100</strong> total visits, comparing two child moves:</p>
214	
215	<ul>
216	  <li><strong>Move X:</strong> n=20, w=15 (75% win rate)</li>
217	  <li><strong>Move Y:</strong> n=5, w=3 (60% win rate)</li>
218	</ul>
219	
220	<p>With C<sub>p</sub> = 1.41 (&radic;2):</p>
221	
222	<table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 0.8rem 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">
223	  <tr style="background:#f0f4ff; border-bottom: 1px solid #d0d9f0;">
224	    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Move</th>
225	    <th style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Exploitation</th>
226	    <th style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Exploration</th>
227	    <th style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">UCT</th>
228	  </tr>
229	  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
230	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">X</td>
231	    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color:#e94560;">15/20 = <strong>0.750</strong></td>
232	    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color:#0f3460;">1.41 &times; &radic;(ln 100 / 20) = <strong>0.484</strong></td>
233	    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; font-weight:700;">1.234</td>
234	  </tr>
235	  <tr>
236	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Y</td>
237	    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color:#e94560;">3/5 = <strong>0.600</strong></td>
238	    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color:#0f3460;">1.41 &times; &radic;(ln 100 / 5) = <strong>0.968</strong></td>
239	    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; font-weight:700;">1.568</td>
240	  </tr>
241	</table>
242	
243	<p><strong>Result:</strong> Move Y is selected even though its win rate is lower. Why? Because it has been visited only 5 times vs. 20 for X — the algorithm is uncertain about Y and wants to gather more data.</p>
244	
245	<div class="callout">
246	  <strong>&#129504; Why this matters for engine design:</strong> In high-branching games like Risk (where a single territory can be attacked from multiple fronts), this behaviour lets the engine try new attack patterns early — even if they look weak — while quickly converging on the statistically strongest lines.
247	</div>
248	
249	<!-- ─── SECTION 5: Tuning Guidelines ─── -->
250	<h2>5. Tuning C<sub>p</sub> for Your Game</h2>
251	
252	<table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 0.8rem 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">
253	  <tr style="background:#16213e; color:#fff;">
254	    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">C<sub>p</sub> Value</th>
255	    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Behaviour</th>
256	    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Best For</th>
257	  </tr>
258	  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
259	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">0</td>
260	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Pure exploitation (greedy)</td>
261	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Late game with few moves left; known-optimal endgames</td>
262	  </tr>
263	  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
264	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">0.5 &ndash; 1.0</td>
265	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Light exploration</td>
266	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Deterministic games with simple rules (Tic-Tac-Toe)</td>
267	  </tr>
268	  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
269	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">1.414 (&radic;2)</td>
270	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">"Goldilocks" default</td>
271	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Most board games; proven optimal for bandit problems</td>
272	  </tr>
273	  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
274	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">2.0 &ndash; 3.0</td>
275	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Heavy exploration</td>
276	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Stochastic games (dice/randomness) where the same move can have varying outcomes</td>
277	  </tr>
278	  <tr>
279	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">&gt; 3.0</td>
280	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Near-random selection</td>
281	    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Early in training; discovering initial strategies</td>
282	  </tr>
283	</table>
284	
285	<!-- ─── SECTION 6: Quiz ─── -->
286	<h2>6. Check Your Understanding</h2>
287	
288	<div class="quiz" id="quiz1">
289	  <h3>&#10003; Quiz: UCT Fundamentals</h3>
290	
291	  <div class="quiz-question" data-q="1">
292	    <p>1. If a child node has n(s,a) = 0 (never visited), what UCT value does it receive?</p>
293	    <div>
294	      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="correct">+&#8734; (infinity)</button>
295	      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">0</button>
296	      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">1</button>
297	    </div>
298	    <div class="quiz-feedback">Correct! An unvisited child always gets priority — the formula divides by zero, treated as +&#8734;. This guarantees every legal move is sampled at least once.</div>
299	  </div>
300	
301	  <div class="quiz-question" data-q="2">
302	    <p>2. What happens to the exploration term &radic;( ln N(s) / n(s,a) ) as n(s,a) increases?</p>
303	    <div>
304	      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">It increases</button>
305	      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="correct">It decreases</button>
306	      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">It stays the same</button>
307	    </div>
308	    <div class="quiz-feedback">Correct! As we visit a child more times, the uncertainty about its true win rate shrinks, so the exploration bonus diminishes. The algorithm shifts from exploration to exploitation.</div>
309	  </div>
310	
311	  <div class="quiz-question" data-q="3">
312	    <p>3. You're designing an engine for Risk (dice-based combat). Should C<sub>p</sub> be higher or lower than the default &radic;2?</p>
313	    <div>
314	      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">Lower</button>
315	      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="correct">Higher</button>
316	      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">Same</button>
317	    </div>
318	    <div class="quiz-feedback">Correct! Risk has randomness (dice rolls), so the same move can produce different outcomes. More exploration (higher C<sub>p</sub>) helps the engine gather enough samples to see past the noise.</div>
319	  </div>
320	</div>
321	
322	<!-- ─── SECTION 7: Summary & Next Steps ─── -->
323	<h2>7. Summary</h2>
324	<ul>
325	  <li>UCT = <span style="color:#e94560;">exploitation (win rate)</span> + <span style="color:#533483;">C<sub>p</sub></span> &times; <span style="color:#0f3460;">exploration bonus (uncertainty)</span></li>
326	  <li>Unvisited children are always selected first (infinite UCT).</li>
327	  <li>Higher C<sub>p</sub> = more exploration; lower = more exploitation.</li>
328	  <li>Stochastic games (dice, cards) benefit from higher C<sub>p</sub>.</li>
329	  <li>Selection is called repeatedly as the first phase of <em>every</em> MCTS iteration.</li>
330	</ul>
331	
332	<p class="cite">
333	  <strong>References:</strong> Kocsis, L. &amp; Szepesvári, C. (2006). <em>Bandit Based Monte-Carlo Planning.</em> ECML 2006.
334	  &bull; Browne, C. et al. (2012). <em>A Survey of Monte Carlo Tree Search Methods.</em> IEEE Trans. CIAG.
335	  &bull; See the <a href="../reference/glossary.html">glossary</a> for full term definitions.
336	</p>
337	
338	<div class="callout">
339	  <strong>&#128172; Questions?</strong> This is just Lesson 0001 — the foundation. If anything is unclear, ask 99 (your teacher) to clarify, walk through more examples, or adjust the pace. The next lesson (0002) will cover <strong>implementing Selection in code</strong>.
340	</div>
341	
342	</div>
343	
344	<script>
345	  (function() {
346	    // ── Interactive C_p Tree Demo ──
347	    const cpSlider = document.getElementById('cp-slider');
348	    const cpValue  = document.getElementById('cp-value');
349	    const children = document.querySelectorAll('.child-node');
350	    const N = 100; // root visits
351	
352	    function updateTree() {
353	      const Cp = parseFloat(cpSlider.value);
354	      cpValue.innerHTML = 'C<sub>p</sub> = ' + Cp.toFixed(1);
355	
356	      let maxUCT = -Infinity;
357	      let bestChild = null;
358	
359	      children.forEach(el => {
360	        const w = parseFloat(el.dataset.wins);
361	        const n = parseFloat(el.dataset.visits);
362	        const exploitation = w / n;
363	        const exploration = Cp * Math.sqrt(Math.log(N) / n);
364	        const uct = exploitation + exploration;
365	        el.querySelector('.uct-val').textContent = 'UCT: ' + uct.toFixed(3);
366	        if (uct > maxUCT) { maxUCT = uct; bestChild = el; }
367	      });
368	
369	      children.forEach(el => el.classList.remove('selected'));
370	      if (bestChild) bestChild.classList.add('selected');
371	    }
372	
373	    cpSlider.addEventListener('input', updateTree);
374	    updateTree();
375	
376	    // ── Quiz Logic ──
377	    document.querySelectorAll('.quiz-btn').forEach(btn => {
378	      btn.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
379	        const question = this.closest('.quiz-question');
380	        const feedback = question.querySelector('.quiz-feedback');
381	        const isCorrect = this.dataset.answer === 'correct';
382	
383	        // Disable all buttons in this question
384	        question.querySelectorAll('.quiz-btn').forEach(b => {
385	          b.disabled = true;
386	          if (b.dataset.answer === 'correct') b.classList.add('correct');
387	          else if (this === b) b.classList.add('wrong');
388	        });
389	
390	        feedback.classList.add('show');
391	        feedback.classList.add(isCorrect ? 'correct' : 'wrong');
392	        feedback.textContent = isCorrect
393	          ? feedback.textContent
394	          : 'Not quite. ' + (feedback.textContent.split('. ').slice(1).join('. ') || 'Try again with the next question.');
395	      });
396	    });
397	  })();
398	</script>
399	</body>
