<div class="container">

<h1>Lesson 0001: The UCT Selection Formula</h1>
<p class="subtitle">The engine at the heart of MCTS — how to choose which branch to explore.</p>

<h2>1. Why Selection Is the Brain of MCTS</h2>
<p>
  In the MCTS cycle, <strong>Selection</strong> is where the algorithm decides <em>which path</em> to descend. A naive selection — always picking the move with the highest win rate — would never discover hidden strengths of unexplored branches. A random selection would be too slow to converge.
</p>
<p>
  The solution is the <strong>UCT</strong> (Upper Confidence Bound applied to Trees) formula. It treats each move from a game state as a <em>multi-armed bandit</em> problem: you have several slot machines (moves), each paying out wins at some unknown rate. UCT tells you which machine to pull next.
</p>

<h2>2. The Three Functions You Need to Know</h2>
<p>
  Before we unpack the formula, let's name every piece. UCT operates on a tree where each <em>node</em> represents a game state, and each <em>edge</em> (parent &rarr; child) represents taking an action <strong>a</strong> from state <strong>s</strong>.
</p>
<table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">
  <tr style="background:#16213e; color:#fff;">
    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Symbol</th>
    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Name</th>
    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">What It Means</th>
  </tr>
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;"><strong>N(s)</strong></td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Parent visit count</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Total times the <em>parent</em> state <em>s</em> has been visited across all MCTS iterations so far.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;"><strong>n(s,a)</strong></td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Child visit count</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Number of times this specific move <em>a</em> was chosen from state <em>s</em>. Starts at 0, increments each time Selection descends into it.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;"><strong>w(s,a)</strong></td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Total reward</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Sum of all rewards (e.g., wins = 1, losses = 0) obtained from simulations that passed through this child. <strong>w(s,a)/n(s,a)</strong> is the empirical win rate.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;"><strong>C<sub>p</sub></strong></td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Exploration constant</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">A tunable parameter (default ≈ √2) that controls how much weight to give exploration vs. exploitation.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>
  So the UCT formula takes these four values and combines them into a single score. The child with the highest UCT score gets selected.
</p>

<h2>3. The UCT Formula (Anatomy)</h2>
<div class="formula-box" id="formula-box">
  UCT(s, a) = <span class="expl-term">w(s,a) / n(s,a)</span> + <span class="explr-term">C<sub>p</sub> &times; &radic;( ln N(s) / n(s,a) )</span>
</div>
<table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #dee2e6;">
    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Term</th>
    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Meaning</th>
    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Role</th>
  </tr>
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color: #e94560;"><strong>w(s,a) / n(s,a)</strong></td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Win rate of action <em>a</em> from state <em>s</em></td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;"><span style="color:#e94560;">Exploitation</span> &mdash; favour moves known to win</td>
  </tr>
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color: #0f3460;"><strong>&radic;( ln N(s) / n(s,a) )</strong></td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Uncertainty bonus &mdash; shrinks as we visit <em>a</em> more</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;"><span style="color:#0f3460;">Exploration</span> &mdash; favour moves tried fewer times</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color: #533483;"><strong>C<sub>p</sub></strong></td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Exploration constant (tunable, default ~&radic;2)</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;"><span style="color:#533483;">Balance</span> &mdash; how much weight to give exploration</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>
  <strong>When n(s,a) = 0</strong> (the move has never been tried), the formula returns +&infin; &mdash; it <em>always</em> selects an unvisited child. This ensures every legal move is sampled at least once before exploitation dominates.
</p>
<div class="callout">
  <strong>&#128161; Key Insight:</strong> The exploration term &radic;( ln N(s) / n(s,a) ) uses the <em>parent's</em> total visits N(s) in the numerator, not the child's. This means a move that looks average but has been visited far fewer times than its siblings gets a large exploration bonus.
</div>

<h2>4. Interactive Demo: Tuning C<sub>p</sub></h2>
<p>
  Below is a root node with four possible moves (A&ndash;D). Each has been visited a different number of times with different win rates. Adjust the <strong>C<sub>p</sub></strong> slider to see which move UCT selects.
</p>
<div class="slider-group">
  <label for="cp-slider">Exploration Constant C<sub>p</sub></label>
  <input type="range" id="cp-slider" min="0" max="5" step="0.1" value="1.41">
  <div class="value-display" id="cp-value">C<sub>p</sub> = 1.41</div>
  <div class="hint">Low (&lt;0.5) = exploit aggressively &nbsp;|&nbsp; High (&gt;3) = explore aggressively</div>
</div>
<div class="tree-viz" id="tree-viz">
  <div class="tree-row">
    <div class="tree-node root-node">
      <div class="label">Root N=165</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="tree-row" id="children-row">
    <div class="tree-node child-node" id="child-A" data-wins="80" data-visits="100">
      <div class="label">Move A</div>
      <div class="stat">w=80 n=100 (80%)</div>
      <div class="uct-val">UCT: &mdash;</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tree-node child-node" id="child-B" data-wins="27" data-visits="40">
      <div class="label">Move B</div>
      <div class="stat">w=27 n=40 (67.5%)</div>
      <div class="uct-val">UCT: &mdash;</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tree-node child-node" id="child-C" data-wins="12" data-visits="20">
      <div class="label">Move C</div>
      <div class="stat">w=12 n=20 (60%)</div>
      <div class="uct-val">UCT: &mdash;</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tree-node child-node" id="child-D" data-wins="2" data-visits="5">
      <div class="label">Move D</div>
      <div class="stat">w=2 n=5 (40%)</div>
      <div class="uct-val">UCT: &mdash;</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="callout">
  <strong>Try it:</strong> Set C<sub>p</sub> = 0. Move A (80% win rate) is selected &mdash; pure exploitation. Now set C<sub>p</sub> to 5.0. Move D (only 5 visits, 40% win rate) gets the highest UCT score because its uncertainty bonus dwarfs the exploitation term. The algorithm chooses to explore the unknown rather than exploit the known.
</div>

<h2>5. Worked Example (By Hand)</h2>
<p>Suppose we're at a root with <strong>N(s) = 100</strong> total visits, comparing two child moves:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Move X:</strong> n=20, w=15 (75% win rate)</li>
  <li><strong>Move Y:</strong> n=5, w=3 (60% win rate)</li>
</ul>
<p>With C<sub>p</sub> = 1.41 (&radic;2):</p>
<table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 0.8rem 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">
  <tr style="background:#f0f4ff; border-bottom: 1px solid #d0d9f0;">
    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Move</th>
    <th style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Exploitation</th>
    <th style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Exploration</th>
    <th style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">UCT</th>
  </tr>
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">X</td>
    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color:#e94560;">15/20 = <strong>0.750</strong></td>
    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color:#0f3460;">1.41 &times; &radic;(ln 100 / 20) = <strong>0.484</strong></td>
    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; font-weight:700;">1.234</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Y</td>
    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color:#e94560;">3/5 = <strong>0.600</strong></td>
    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; color:#0f3460;">1.41 &times; &radic;(ln 100 / 5) = <strong>0.968</strong></td>
    <td style="text-align:center; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem; font-weight:700;">1.568</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Result:</strong> Move Y is selected even though its win rate is lower. Why? Because it has been visited only 5 times vs. 20 for X &mdash; the algorithm is uncertain about Y and wants to gather more data.</p>
<div class="callout">
  <strong>&#129504; Why this matters for engine design:</strong> In high-branching games like Risk (where a single territory can be attacked from multiple fronts), this behaviour lets the engine try new attack patterns early &mdash; even if they look weak &mdash; while quickly converging on the statistically strongest lines.
</div>

<h2>6. Tuning C<sub>p</sub> for Your Game</h2>
<table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 0.8rem 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">
  <tr style="background:#16213e; color:#fff;">
    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">C<sub>p</sub> Value</th>
    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Behaviour</th>
    <th style="text-align:left; padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Best For</th>
  </tr>
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">0</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Pure exploitation (greedy)</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Late game with few moves left; known-optimal endgames</td>
  </tr>
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">0.5 &ndash; 1.0</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Light exploration</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Deterministic games with simple rules (Tic-Tac-Toe)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">1.414 (&radic;2)</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">"Goldilocks" default</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Most board games; proven optimal for bandit problems</td>
  </tr>
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">2.0 &ndash; 3.0</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Heavy exploration</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Stochastic games (dice/randomness) where the same move can have varying outcomes</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">&gt; 3.0</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Near-random selection</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.4rem 0.5rem;">Early in training; discovering initial strategies</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h2>7. Check Your Understanding</h2>
<div class="quiz" id="quiz1">
  <h3>&#10003; Quiz: UCT Fundamentals</h3>
  <div class="quiz-question" data-q="1">
    <p>1. If a child node has n(s,a) = 0 (never visited), what UCT value does it receive?</p>
    <div>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="correct">+&#8734; (infinity)</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">0</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">1</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback">Correct! An unvisited child always gets priority &mdash; the formula divides by zero, treated as +&#8734;. This guarantees every legal move is sampled at least once.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz-question" data-q="2">
    <p>2. What happens to the exploration term &radic;( ln N(s) / n(s,a) ) as n(s,a) increases?</p>
    <div>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">It increases</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="correct">It decreases</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">It stays the same</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback">Correct! As we visit a child more times, the uncertainty about its true win rate shrinks, so the exploration bonus diminishes. The algorithm shifts from exploration to exploitation.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="quiz-question" data-q="3">
    <p>3. You're designing an engine for Risk (dice-based combat). Should C<sub>p</sub> be higher or lower than the default &radic;2?</p>
    <div>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">Lower</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="correct">Higher</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">Same</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback">Correct! Risk has randomness (dice rolls), so the same move can produce different outcomes. More exploration (higher C<sub>p</sub>) helps the engine gather enough samples to see past the noise.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<h2>8. Summary</h2>
<ul>
  <li>UCT = <span style="color:#e94560;">exploitation (win rate)</span> + <span style="color:#533483;">C<sub>p</sub></span> &times; <span style="color:#0f3460;">exploration bonus (uncertainty)</span></li>
  <li>Unvisited children are always selected first (infinite UCT).</li>
  <li>Higher C<sub>p</sub> = more exploration; lower = more exploitation.</li>
  <li>Stochastic games (dice, cards) benefit from higher C<sub>p</sub>.</li>
  <li>Selection is called repeatedly as the first phase of <em>every</em> MCTS iteration.</li>
</ul>
<p class="cite">
  <strong>References:</strong> Kocsis, L. &amp; Szepesvári, C. (2006). <em>Bandit Based Monte-Carlo Planning.</em> ECML 2006.
  &bull; Browne, C. et al. (2012). <em>A Survey of Monte Carlo Tree Search Methods.</em> IEEE Trans. CIAG.
  &bull; See the <a href="../reference/glossary.html">glossary</a> for full term definitions.
</p>
<div class="callout">
  <strong>&#128172; Questions?</strong> This is just Lesson 0001 &mdash; the foundation. If anything is unclear, ask 99 (your teacher) to clarify, walk through more examples, or adjust the pace. The next lesson (0002) will cover <strong>implementing Selection in code</strong>.
</div>

</div>

<script>
  (function() {
    var cpSlider = document.getElementById('cp-slider');
    var cpValue  = document.getElementById('cp-value');
    var children = document.querySelectorAll('.child-node');
    var N = 165;

    function updateTree() {
      var Cp = parseFloat(cpSlider.value);
      cpValue.innerHTML = 'C<sub>p</sub> = ' + Cp.toFixed(1);

      var maxUCT = -Infinity;
      var bestChild = null;

      children.forEach(function(el) {
        var w = parseFloat(el.dataset.wins);
        var n = parseFloat(el.dataset.visits);
        var exploitation = w / n;
        var exploration = Cp * Math.sqrt(Math.log(N) / n);
        var uct = exploitation + exploration;
        el.querySelector('.uct-val').textContent = 'UCT: ' + uct.toFixed(3);
        if (uct > maxUCT) { maxUCT = uct; bestChild = el; }
      });

      children.forEach(function(el) { el.classList.remove('selected'); });
      if (bestChild) bestChild.classList.add('selected');
    }

    cpSlider.addEventListener('input', updateTree);
    updateTree();

    document.querySelectorAll('.quiz-btn').forEach(function(btn) {
      btn.addEventListener('click', function() {
        var question = this.closest('.quiz-question');
        var feedback = question.querySelector('.quiz-feedback');
        var isCorrect = this.dataset.answer === 'correct';

        question.querySelectorAll('.quiz-btn').forEach(function(b) {
          b.disabled = true;
          if (b.dataset.answer === 'correct') b.classList.add('correct');
          else if (this === b) b.classList.add('wrong');
        });

        feedback.classList.add('show');
        feedback.classList.add(isCorrect ? 'correct' : 'wrong');
      });
    });
  })();
</script>
</body>
