<body>
<div class="container">

<h1>Lesson 0003: Expansion and Simulation</h1>
<p class="subtitle">Adding nodes to the tree and running rollouts &mdash; phases 2 and 3 of the MCTS cycle.</p>

<h2>1. The Flow After Selection</h2>
<p>
    Recall from Lesson 0002 that <tt>tree_policy</tt> returns a node at the frontier &mdash; either a node that <em>isn't fully expanded</em> (has untried moves) or a <em>terminal</em> node. What happens next depends on which case we're in:
</p>

<div class="figure-box">
    <strong>tree_policy result</strong><br>
    &#9507;&#9472; Not fully expanded &rarr; <strong>Expansion:</strong> add one new child node<br>
    &#9499;&#9472; Terminal &rarr; <strong>Skip Expansion</strong> (no moves to make)
</div>

<div class="code-block">
<span class="cm"># Inside mcts_iteration (from Lesson 0002):</span>
node = <span class="fn">tree_policy</span>(root, Cp)   <span class="cm"># Selection phase</span>

<span class="kw">if</span> <span class="kw">not</span> node.is_terminal:
    node = <span class="fn">expand</span>(node)           <span class="cm"># Expansion phase (NEW)</span>

reward = <span class="fn">simulate</span>(node)          <span class="cm"># Simulation phase (NEW)</span>
</div>

<h2>2. Expansion: Growing the Tree</h2>

<p>
    <strong>Expansion</strong> is deceptively simple: take one untried move from the current node, apply it to produce a new game state, wrap that state in a new <tt>MCTSNode</tt>, link it as a child, and return it.
</p>

<div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">expand</span>(node):
    <span class="cm">"""Pick one untried move, create a child node, and return it."""</span>
    <span class="cm"># Pop one untried move (order matters &mdash; first legal move, first tried)</span>
    move = node.untried_moves.<span class="fn">pop</span>()

    <span class="cm"># Apply the move to get a new state</span>
    new_state = node.state.<span class="fn">apply</span>(move)

    <span class="cm"># Create the child node, link it to parent</span>
    child = <span class="cls">MCTSNode</span>(new_state, parent=node)
    node.children.<span class="fn">append</span>(child)

    <span class="kw">return</span> child
</div>

<div class="callout-info">
    <strong>&#128161; Design choice: one child per call.</strong> We expand exactly <em>one</em> child per iteration, not all of them. This is the standard approach &mdash; it keeps each MCTS iteration cheap and lets UCT guide which branches get deepened first. Over many iterations, all moves eventually get expanded.
</div>

<p>
    The <tt>state.apply(move)</tt> method is game-specific. In Chess it would make a move on the board. In Risk it would resolve a combat and advance the game state. For <strong>stochastic games</strong> (games with random elements), <tt>apply</tt> must also handle chance events &mdash; more on this in a future lesson.
</p>

<h2>3. Simulation / Rollout: The Monte Carlo Step</h2>

<p>
    <strong>Simulation</strong> (also called <strong>rollout</strong>) is where the "Monte Carlo" name comes from. From the node returned by Expansion (or directly from Selection if the node was terminal), we play a <em>full game</em> to completion using a fast, simple policy &mdash; typically random moves. The result is a single reward signal: $+1$ for a win, $0$ for a loss, $+0.5$ for a draw.
</p>

<div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">simulate</span>(node):
    <span class="cm">"""Run a random rollout from this node's state to a terminal.</span>
<span class="cm">       Returns the reward from the perspective of the player who</span>
<span class="cm">       made the move that led to this node."""</span>
    state = node.state.<span class="fn">clone</span>()      <span class="cm"># don't mutate the tree's state</span>

    <span class="kw">while</span> <span class="kw">not</span> state.<span class="fn">is_terminal</span>():
        move = <span class="fn">random_choice</span>(state.<span class="fn">legal_moves</span>())
        state.<span class="fn">apply</span>(move)

    <span class="kw">return</span> state.<span class="fn">reward</span>()          <span class="cm"># +1, 0, or 0.5 from current player's perspective</span>
</div>

<h3>3.1 Why Random Works</h3>
<p>
    Intuitively, random play seems useless &mdash; how can a random game tell us anything about a good move? The key insight is that we're not relying on <em>one</em> simulation but on <em>the aggregate of many</em>. If move A leads to a win in 65% of random rollouts and move B wins only 35%, then A is genuinely the better move &mdash; even though each individual rollout was random chaos.
</p>

<div class="callout-design">
    <strong>&#129504; Tradeoff: Rollout Policy Quality vs. Speed</strong><br><br>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Rollout Policy</th><th>Quality per Rollout</th><th>Rollouts per Second</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Uniform random</td><td>Low (noisy)</td><td>Very high</td><td>Games with shallow trees; prototyping</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Heuristic-guided</td><td>Medium (biased)</td><td>Medium</td><td>Games with good heuristic rules (e.g., capture pieces in Chess)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Light playouts</td><td>High (domain-aware)</td><td>Low</td><td>Fine-tuning a near-complete engine</td></tr>
    </table>
    <br>
    The surprising result from the literature: uniform random is often <em>good enough</em> for MCTS to outperform hand-crafted AIs, because the statistical aggregation across thousands of rollouts washes out the noise. This is what made the original MCTS (before neural nets) so powerful.
</div>

<h3>3.2 Cloning vs. Applying</h3>
<p>
    Notice that <tt>simulate</tt> calls <tt>state.clone()</tt> before making moves. This is critical: the rollout mutates the state (applying random moves), but we must not mutate the state stored inside our <tt>MCTSNode</tt> tree. The clone creates an independent copy for the rollout.
</p>

<div class="callout">
    <strong>&#9888;&#65039; Watch out!</strong> If your game state is expensive to clone (e.g., a large board with many pieces), consider a <em>copy-on-write</em> or <em>undo</em> pattern: apply a move for the rollout, then undo it. This avoids cloning overhead at the cost of more careful code.
</div>

<h2>4. Whose Perspective Is the Reward From?</h2>
<p>
    A subtle but critical question: when we win a simulation, who gets credit? The reward must be from the perspective of the <strong>player who made the move</strong> that led to the current node, not from the perspective of the simulator.
</p>

<p>
    For a two-player zero-sum game (Chess, Go), a win for the current player is $+1$ for them and $0$ for the opponent. During Backpropagation, we alternate the reward sign as we move up the tree &mdash; because what's good for the current player is bad for the parent. We'll cover this in Lesson 0004.
</p>

<p>
    But there's another approach that simplifies things enormously: <strong>no-perspective rewards</strong>, where you always backpropagate the raw result. This works because the sign flip happens at each level of the tree naturally &mdash; you just negate the reward on each step up. We'll see the code for both approaches in Lesson 0004.
</p>

<h2>5. Expansion + Simulation Worked Example</h2>
<p>
    Let's trace through one iteration on a hypothetical game tree:
</p>

<div class="figure-box">
    <strong>Before iteration:</strong> Root (N=50) has children A (n=20, w=15), B (n=30, w=12).<br>
    UCT selects A (exploitation 0.75 + exploration ...). A has <em>one untried move</em> remaining.
</div>

<div class="code-block">
<span class="cm">// 1. tree_policy descends to A (not fully expanded, stops)</span>
<span class="cm">// 2. expand(A): pops the last untried move, applies it -&gt; new child C</span>
A.children <span class="op">=</span> [old_child1, old_child2, <span class="cls">C</span>]
A.untried_moves <span class="op">=</span> []

<span class="cm">// 3. simulate(C): random rollout from C's state</span>
<span class="cm">//    Result: win for C's player -&gt; reward = +1</span>
</div>

<div class="callout-info">
    <strong>&#128161; Note:</strong> After expansion, we simulate from the <em>new child</em> C, not from A. This is the standard pattern &mdash; the rollout starts from the state we just expanded to.
</div>

<h2>6. Check Your Understanding</h2>

<div class="quiz" id="quiz1">
  <h3>&#10003; Quiz: Expansion and Simulation</h3>

  <div class="quiz-question" data-q="1">
    <p>1. How many children does <tt>expand()</tt> create per call?</p>
    <div>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">All untried moves at once</button>
