    <div>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="correct">To avoid mutating the state stored inside the tree</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">To make the rollout faster</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">To ensure the rollout is deterministic</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback">Correct! The rollout mutates the game state (applying random moves). If we didn't clone, we'd corrupt the node's state, breaking the tree for all future iterations.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="quiz-question" data-q="3">
    <p>3. A rollout using uniform random moves wins 55% of the time for move X. Is X likely the best move?</p>
    <div>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">No, random play is meaningless</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="correct">Probably yes, if the sample size is large enough</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">Only if the opponent also plays randomly</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback">Correct! The aggregate of many random rollouts provides a useful signal. If move X wins 55% vs. the alternatives at 40%, it's genuinely stronger &mdash; the statistical noise washes out with enough samples.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="quiz-question" data-q="4">
    <p>4. What happens after <tt>tree_policy</tt> returns a terminal node?</p>
    <div>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">The iteration stops and starts over</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="correct">Expansion is skipped, simulation returns the known result</button>
      <button class="quiz-btn" data-answer="wrong">The terminal node is expanded with a "pass" move</button>
    </div>
    <div class="quiz-feedback">Correct! No moves to expand from a terminal state. The simulation just returns the known terminal reward &mdash; no random rollout needed.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<h2>7. Summary</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Expansion</strong> pops one untried move, applies it to create a new <tt>MCTSNode</tt>, and links it as a child.</li>
